We recorded co-infections by multiple pathogens (two or three viruses) across the three families, representing 37.9 % (22/58) of the sampled species. CPV was the most frequent virus involved in mixed infections with nucleic acid from additional viruses detected in 95.5 % (21/22) of the co-infected individuals. Among these, CCoV mixed infections with CPV were most common in both wolves and red foxes (
 Fig. 3 ; 
 Table 5 ). Unfortunately for most mixed infections, there was no information on the cause of death or any additional data that could help with the diagnosis.
